\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 Elrahet - how do I taste?}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 I first learned the facts from a lunatic\line In a dark and quiet room that smelled of stale time and space\line There are no people\line Nothing at all like that\line The human phenomenon is but the sum of densely coiled layers of illusion\line Each of which winds itself upon the supreme insanity\line But there are persons of any kind\line When all that can be is mindless mirrors\line Laughing and screaming as they parade about\line In an endless dream }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 In his study The Nature of Evil (1931), Radoslav A. Tsanoff cites a terse reflection set down by the German philosopher Julius Bahnsen in 1847, when he was seventeen years old. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Man is a self-conscious Nothing,\u8221\'94 declared the young man. Bahnsen was not, of course, the first to arrive at a dour appraisal of his own kind. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Anyone pursuing an audience, or even a place in society, might profit from the following motto: \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93If you can\u8217\'92t say something positive about our species, then say something equivocal.\u8221\'94 These facts, in themselves, are neither cause to ridicule the judgment of the majority nor grounds for conforming to it uncritically. Tending toward the negativity of the latter mind-set, Bahnsen went too far, as if to assure himself a lasting obscurity. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 I need to get at the dim awareness of all the people who have met an untimely death. We soldier on.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 In the words of British author and Christian apologist G. K. Chesterton, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You can only find truth with logic if you have already found truth without it.\u8221\'94 (Example: every debate over the existence of God is won by His defenders.)\~ }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Man is a self-conscious Nothing.\u8221\'94 Taken at face value, this statement is a paradox and a horror. Being self-conscious and being nothing should rule out each other. Instead they are coupled to suggest an unreal monstrosity, an existential chimera on the order of the}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93undead.\u8221\'94 The greater community of self-conscious mortals will tell you they are something, not nothing. The suicidal will tell you they are something but wish they were nothing. What almost no one will tell you is that they \u8220\'93know\u8221\'94 they are nothing\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 living puppets helpless to act except as bidden by powers unseen\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 but, being self-conscious, suffer the illusion that they are something. They believe this is how it is with everyone\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 that all of us are living the same paradox, the same horror. They also believe we will do anything to keep this knowledge out of our heads because if we did not, how could we go on living? And why would we replenish the world with more self-conscious nothings, more puppets?}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Take a moment to consider the puppet. It is an object made somewhat in our image that does not know what we know . . . or believe ourselves to know, which amounts to the same thing. Undeniably, our minds have wanton moments when a puppet seems as if it can come to life, hop up like a human being, know things that we know and perhaps other things that we do not. Then an insoluble psychological conflict erupts, a dissonance of perception that sends a tremor of supernatural horror through our being. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Through the prophylactic of self-illusion, we hide from what we fear to let into our heads. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 But puppets have nothing to hide. They are more than willing to betray a secret too terrible for us to know. Our lives are full of baffling questions that virtuosos of speculation trifle with and the rest of us forget about. Naked apes or embodied angels we perhaps may be, but not self-conscious nothings. We are somebodies who move freely about and think what we choose. Puppets are not like that. They have nothing in their heads. They are unreal. When they are in motion, we know they are moved by an outside force. When they speak, their voices come from elsewhere. Their orders come from somewhere behind and beyond them. And were they ever to become aware of that fact, they would collapse at the horror of it all, as would we. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 All supernatural horror depends on a confusion of what we believe should be and should not be.\~ }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 But to all appearances, thank God and nature, there is nothing to worry about. Almost everyone believes we are natural beings whose lives have an inborn value. No one can prove that our existence is a paradox and a horror. Everything is all right with the world. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Although no solid answers seem impending on the broader questions presented by consciousness, there is general assent on its main effect: to make human beings the only creatures who know they are alive and know they will die. From this knowledge, everything that separates us from other life-forms derives. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Being alive is all right.\u8221\'94 More thoughtful respondents will add, \u8220\'93Especially when you consider the alternative,\u8221\'94 betraying a jocularity that is as logically puzzling as it is macabre.\~ }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 They may even fulminate that being alive is objectionable and useless on principle.\~ }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Were there any choice on our part about what we think and feel, it would not be adventurous to conjecture that we would think only as needed and choose to feel good as appropriate. Some might choose to live in a permanent state of intense euphoria. With godlike power over your thoughts and moods, why hold back? }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Such control would permit us, by fiat of self-addlement, to be careless of every hideous fact that our consciousness may impart about life and death. What is more, those who say that being alive is all right and those who aver the opposite would become united rather divided: we all do what we can to lock out what being alive implies, whichever side of the issue we may be on. And since we have no power of veto over our birth, we could choose to be ecstatic about it rather than negative. We would all be on the same side if we had absolute control over any lethal knowledge that might come into our heads. But the best we can do is this: stay as stupid as we can for as long as we can. And some people can stay just so stupid for just so long. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Being alive\u8221\'94 encompasses such an abounding medley of feelings and sensations that it means nothing to say one knows anything about it. We may think of ourselves as \u8220\'93being alive\u8221\'94 in moments of exhilaration or well being, yet we have no smaller portion of life in us when we are depressed or are suffering in some other style. And if we are not suffering at present\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 or at least not suffering noticeably\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 it is insurmountably difficult to know what suffering is like, or what it was once like for us in the past as well as what it will be like in the future. As for knowing that we will die, our ignorance is absolute, now and forever. We can only fear death without knowing anything about what we fear. Some people can short-circuit their jitters about public speaking by exposing themselves to it repeatedly. But no mortal can overcome the fear of death with practice.\~ }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 AI we are encumbering it with the inability to choose what to think about. We are its environment. It navigates us.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The butcher, the baker, and the crushing majority of philosophers all agree on one thing: human life is splendidly justified, and its continuance by means of biological reproduction should be forever in vogue. To tout the opposing side is asking for trouble vis-\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u224\'E0-vis a world in which all commerce depends on handshakes and smiles.\~ }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Among such efforts is a treatise whose title has been rendered into English as On the Tragic (1941). Written by the Norwegian philosopher and man of letters Peter Wessel Zapffe (1899-1990), On the Tragic has not appeared in any major language at the time of this writing. By some fluke or fortune, however, Zapffe\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s essay \u8220\'93The Last Messiah\u8221\'94 (1933), which broadly sketches the principles of his masterwork, has been twice been translated into English }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Rigorously considered, our only natural birthright is to die.) No other rights have been allocated to us except, to repeat with emphasis, as fabrications.4 The divine right of kings may now be acknowledged as such a fabrication\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 a falsified permit for prideful dementia and arbitrary mayhem. The unalienable rights of certain people, however, seemingly remain current: whether observed or violated, somehow we believe they are not fabrications because an old document says they are real. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Miserly or munificent as a given right may appear, it denotes no more than the right of way warranted by a traffic light, which does not mean you have the right to drive free of vehicular mishaps. Ask any paramedic. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~tragedy entered the human scene only after our wayward heads began to gyrate with consciousness and self-consciousness: }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 We are the species that knows too much to content ourselves with merely surviving, reproducing, dying\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 and nothing else. We want there to be more to it than that, or to think there is. This is the tragedy: consciousness has forced us into the paradoxical position of uselessly striving to be something other than what we are\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 hunks of spoiling flesh on crumbling bones.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 we thwart it in four principle ways: (1) by isolation of the dire facts of existence from our minds, denying both to ourselves and to others (in a conspiracy of silence) that our condition is inherently disconcerting and problematic; (2) by anchoring our lives in metaphysical and institutional \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93verities\u8221\'94\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 God, Country, Family, Laws\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 based on charters issued by an enforcing authority (in the same way as a hunting license), imbuing us with a sense of being official, authentic, and guarded while shunting aside the feeling that these documents are not worth the paper they are written on (in the same way as a passport establishes one\u8217\'92s identity even though it may be forged); (3) by distraction, a widespread conspiracy in which everyone keeps their eyes on the ball\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 or a television screen or fireworks display\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 and their heads placidly unreflective; (4) by sublimation, the process by which thinkers and artistic types recycle the most demoralizing and unnerving aspects of life as works in which the worst fortunes of humanity are represented in a stylized and removed manner for the purposes of edification and entertainment, forming the conspiracy of creating and consuming products that provide an escape from our suffering in the guise of a false confrontation with it\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 a tragic drama or philosophical woolgathering, for instance. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 These tactics keep our imaginations from scrutinizing too closely the smorgasbord of pains and death-agonies laid out for us. Alongside these corporeal unpleasantries is the abstract abashment some persons suffer because, at the end of the day, they feel their lives are destitute of any meaning or purpose }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 As posited above, consciousness may have facilitated our species\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92 survival in the hard times of prehistory, but as it became evermore acute it evolved the potential to ruin everything if not held firmly in check. Therefore, we must either outsmart consciousness or drown in its vortex of doleful factuality. Given this premise, Zapffe makes his second proposition, which is that the sensible thing to do would be to call off all procreative activities, thereby stamping out what has often been called the \u8220\'93curse of consciousness.\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 To repeat: we can tolerate existence only if we believe\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 in accord with a complex of illusions, a legerdemain of impenetrable deception\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 that we are not what we are.\~ }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 In plain language, we cannot live with ourselves except as impostors. As Zapffe points out in \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The Last Messiah,\u8221\'94 this is the paradox of the human: the impossibility of not lying to ourselves 19}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 about ourselves and about our no-win situation in this world. Thus, we are zealots of the four strategies delineated above: isolation (\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Being alive is all right\u8221\'94), anchoring (\u8220\'93One Nation under God with Families and Laws for all\u8221\'94), distraction (\u8220\'93Better to kill time than kill oneself\u8221\'94), and sublimation (\u8220\'93I am writing a book titled The Conspiracy against the Human Race\u8221\'94).\~}
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Without this cognitive double-dealing, being alive would bare itself as a sordid burlesque and not the fabulous thing we thought it was. Maybe then we would know what it is to be human instead of just puppets beating the boards and one another.\~ }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 But you see, he is missing a critical component - We are born and we die, yes, but there is also sensation.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Being royally conscious of the solemn precincts in which we exist, of the savage wasteland that lies beneath all the piddling nonsense, would turn our world in on its head. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 We can pretend this will not happen, fantasizing super-scientific eternities, but in good time we will be taken out of the scene. This turn of events will be the defeat of Project Immortality, which has been in the works for millennia. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Without a terminus imposed on our lifetimes, their 20}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \line }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 uselessness would become excruciatingly overt. Knowing ourselves to be on a collision course with the Wall of Death may be a horror, but it is the only thing that makes it possible to value that which comes before. While this quid pro quo may be a bad value, without it there is no value, for those who care. The eternal afterlife awaiting some of us on the other side of the wall is, quite naturally, only another end-of-the-line established to make this life valuable . . . or at least livable, which amounts to the same thing.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 if only you knew how horrible the long of nothingnessi s, you would long for the gas chamber. Unending bliss is nothingness. A white blur. It\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s unacceptable \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0  God here seems human}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~Others must be satisfied with mere driblets of value that stream thinly back from a terminal point in death or immortality.\~ }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Neither of Zapffe\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s main propositions\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 the mistake of consciousness or the corrective of shutting down the assembly line of reproduction\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 is exclusive to his philosophy.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Buddhism has long preached that ordinary consciousness is the greatest roadblock to the deliverance of human beings from the crucible of existence. In his Tragic Sense of Life in Men and Nations (1913), the Spanish writer Miguel de Unamuno speaks of consciousness as a disease bred by a conflict between the rational and the irrational. The irrational represents all that is vital in humanity, including a universal desire for immortality. The rational is identified with the conclusions of consciousness, primarily that we will all die. The coexistence of the rational and the irrational turns the human experience into a wrangle of contradictions to which we can submit with a suicidal resignation or obstinately defy as heroes of futility. (Unamuno\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s penchant is for heroic course with the implied precondition that one has the physical and psychological spunk for the fight: \u8220\'93I think, therefore I will die; but I cannot let that keep me from acting as if I did not think.\u8221\'94) The contradiction between the rational and the irrational in Unamuno\u8217\'92s Tragic Sense of Life is echoed by French existentialist superstar Albert Camus as the}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Absurd\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 On the scientific side there is mismatch theory. This subsidiary concept of evolutionary psychology studies characteristics of our species that were once adaptive but have since become inimical to surviving in the environment we have made for ourselves. The same idea was cited by Theodore Kaczynski (a.k.a. The Unabomber) as a rationalization for the mayhem he committed in his one-man war on technological \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93advancement.\u8221\'94 The combination of our species\u8217\'92 aggressive nature with its relatively recent leap in consciousness and intellect was incarnated by Kaczynski himself, whose sophisticated brain and violent actions fit like a velvet glove in a chain mail gauntlet. Another luminary of \u8220\'93civilization,\u8221\'94 the British physicist Stephen Hawking, has also alleged that our vigorous exercise of conscious thought without a counterbalancing diminution of aggression is a formula for 21}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \line }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 disaster. In the immemorial past, the cocktail of intelligence and ferocity gave us a leg up on the predatory competition, but it has since become a real powder keg of perils, not to mention being the nucleus of those psychological discontents popularized by Sigmund Freud.9}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 In his 1910 doctoral dissertation, published in English as Persuasion and Rhetoric (2004), the twenty-three-year-old Italian philosopher Carlo Michelstaedter vehemently critiqued, very much in same terms as Zapffe, the maneuvers by which we falsify the realities of human existence in exchange for a speciously comforting view of our lives.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Michelstaedter\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s biographers and critics have speculated that his hopelessness regarding any person\u8217\'92s ability to break through their web of illusions was the cause of his suicide (two bullets from a gun) the day after he finished his dissertation. Other examples could be offered of serious philosophers and intellectuals who have observed that, while officially we crow about our brain-to-body ratio, much of our time is spent trying to keep that beast in our skulls well sedated. Few thinkers\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 by definition, one would have to say\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 have been untroubled by our self-awareness.}
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 But individuals are defined by their limitations; without them, they fall outside the barrier of identifiable units, functionaries in the big show of collective existence, attach\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u233\'E9s to the human species. The farther you proceed toward a vision of humankind under the aspect of eternity, the farther you drift from what makes you a person among persons in this world. In the observance of Zapffe, an overactive consciousness endangers the approving way in which we define ourselves and our lives. It does this by threatening our self-limited perception of who we are and what it means to know we are alive and will die. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The Gnostic sect of the Cathari in twelfth-century France were so tenacious in believing the world to be an evil place engendered by an evil deity that its members were offered a dual ultimatum: sexual abstinence or sodomy. (A similar sect in Bulgaria, the Bogomils, became the etymological source of the term \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93bugger\u8221\'94 for their adherence to the latter practice.) While mandated abstinence for clerics was around the same time embedded in the doctrines of the Catholic Church, even though they betimes give in to sexual quickening, its raison d\u8217\'92\u234\'EAtre was said to be the attainment of grace (and in legend was a requisite for those in search of the Holy Grail) rather than to speed the extinction of humanity.\~}
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 And if we are mistaken about consciousness being a mistake, our self-removal from this planet would still be a magnificent move on our part, the most laudable masterstroke of our existence . . . and the only one. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Hedonism will not wash as a justification for our existence. No price is too high for our creaturely reward of just being here and knowing that others will be here after us. This is our \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93pleasure,\u8221\'94 and no pain will lead our species to question it. If this pleasure began in biology, it now stems primarily from psychological satisfactions. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 And how many have deterred their minds from real torture by derealizing it in paintings, music, or words because they could not abide this consciousness (sublimation)? }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The earth is not our home. We came from nothing, and to that condition our nostalgia should turn. Why would anyone care about this dim bulb in the blackness of space? The earth produced us, or at least subsidized our evolution. Is it really entitled to receive a pardon, let alone the sacrifice of human lives, for this original sin\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 a capital crime in reverse (very much in the same way that reproduction makes one an accessory before the fact to an individual\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s death)? Someone once said that nature abhors a vacuum. This is precisely why nature should be abhorred. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 There is a theory that the creation of the human species is nature\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s roundabout way of cutting into its veins and bleeding out.14 A strange idea, no protesting that, but not the strangest we have ever heard or lived by. We could at least assume the theory and see where it leads. If it is false, then where is the harm? }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 From a human vantage, would this not be a just self-punishment by nature for fashioning a world in which pain is essential, a world that could not exist without pain, a world where pain is the guiding principle of all organisms, which are relentlessly pushed by pain throughout their lives to do that which will improve their chances of surviving long enough to create more of themselves? Left unchecked, this process will last as long as a single cell is left quivering in this cesspool of the solar system, this toilet of the galaxy. So why not lend a hand in nature\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s eradication, in case it has second thoughts? For want of a deity, let the earth take the blame for our troubles. What else is it good for?\~ \~Let it save itself if it can\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 the condemned are known for the acrobatics they will perform to wriggle out of their sentences\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 but if it cannot destroy what it has made, then may it perish along with every other living thing it has brought forth in pain. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
